'''Woz U''' is a tech education platform launched by [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] co-founder [[Steve Wozniak]] that focuses on both students and companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/10/13/steve-wozniak-announces-tech-education-platform-woz-u/|title=Steve Wozniak announces tech education platform Woz U|last=Crook|first=Jordan|work=TechCrunch|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en}}</ref> Woz U is Arizona-based with plans to launch physical locations for learning in more than 30 cities across the globe.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20171013005008/en/Apple-Co-Founder-Steve-Wozniak-Forms-Woz-Reprogram|title=Apple Co-Founder Steve Wozniak Forms 'Woz U' to Reprogram Tech Education, Address Skills Gap|website=www.businesswire.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/10/13/16474170/apple-steve-wozniak-woz-u-launch-tech-education-online-university|title=Apple co-founder Steve Wozniak launches his own online tech education platform|work=The Verge|access-date=2017-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/13/steve-wozniak-created-online-university/|title=Steve Wozniak just created his own online university|work=Engadget|access-date=2017-10-14|language=en-US}}</ref> Although the company is registered in Arizona,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ecorp.azcc.gov/BusinessSearch/BusinessInformation?businessId=885230|title=WOZ U EDUCATION LLC  - Arizona Corporations Commission|last=|first=|date=|website=ecorp.azcc.gov|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-10-13}}</ref> it works through its Texas-based partner, [[Southern Careers Institute|Southern Careers Institute.]] Less than a week after the launch announcement, the company came under scrutiny by state regulators about the lack of state accreditation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-education/2017/10/18/woz-u-arizona-state-regulators-have-questions-key-paperwork-unfinished/773509001/|title=Woz U: AZ state regulators have questions, key paperwork unfinished|last=Jeong|first=Yihyun|date=2017-10-18|work=azcentral|access-date=2018-10-13|last2=Ryman|first2=Anne|language=en}}</ref>

In fall of 2018, a CBS News investigation of Woz U cast some doubts on the professionalism of the expensive curriculum. CBS interviewed two dozen current and former students and employees, who shared their dissatisfaction with the content quality, such as documentation typos leading to confusing program errors, while some promised live lectures were actually recorded and out-of-date. One student described the 33-week online program as "a $13,000 e-book". A former "enrollment counselor" described a high-pressure sales environment, which the company denied. In a prepared statement, Woz U president Chris Coleman admitted the documentation errors and said quality control efforts were being implemented, and said curriculum was reviewed by Wozniak. The founder declined interview requests, then dodged a reporter's unannounced appearance at a conference.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/woz-u-steve-wozniak-former-students-employees-raise-concerns/|title=Some former students, employees say Apple co-founder's Woz U doesn't live up to promises|last=|first=|date=2018-10-01|work=CBS News|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/steve-wozniaks-woz-u-is-a-13000-e-book-former-students-say/|title=Steve Wozniak’s Woz U is 'a $13,000 e-book,' former students say|last=Zhou|first=Marrian|date=2018-10-01|work=CNET|access-date=2018-10-13|language=en}}</ref>

